# Div Element

HTML elements allow you to group together content on your web page that is connected. However sometimes you want to group together multiple HTML elements into one connected chunk and give it a style.  To connect a set of HTML elements inside one element you can use the `<div>` element.

For your Personal Website you are going to start out by using this to group together the header section you want to go on every page of your website. This will include the title of your website as well as any navigation. Once you do this you can put a background color on the whole div to make it look like one connected block.

<pre>
&lt;div&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt; Title of Website &lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;a href="index.html"&gt; Home &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;a href="page1.html"&gt; Page 1 &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;a href="page2.html"&gt; Page 1 &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;a href="page3.html"&gt; Page 1&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</pre>

# Do This

* Put all the navigation hyperlinks and page title in `<div>` element
* Add a `background-color` for the `<div>` element

markdown_instructions.CSDU2 - Priority of CSS Rules_markdown_i:
# Priority of CSS Rules

On the last level you moved all the style rules to one style.css file that is linked to both web pages on the website. You may have noticed that the way some of the styling of the elements on the two pages changed. Over the next couple levels you will be working to fix this.

## Multiple Rules for One Element

By copying the style rules from two different pages into one style sheet we created a couple cases where we have two style rules for one element. Style rules are applied from top to bottom so when there are multiple style-rules for the same properties of one element the one closer to the bottom is the one that will appear.

For example if you had the following style rules.

<pre>
p{
  background-color: blue;
}
p{
  background-color: red;
}
</pre>

The pargraph elements would have a red background.

To fix this issue the best thing to do is have one rule for each type of element.

# Do This

* There are two style rules for `<div>` elements. They are both the same. Delete one of them.
* There are two style rules for `<body>` elements. They are **different** but both just control the `background-color` decide which of the two you would like to keep and get rid of the other one.
* Leave the duplicate `<img>` element style rules for now we will deal with them on the next level.

markdown_instructions.CSDU2 - head body_markdown_instruction:
# Head and Body

There are now two different sections of code in our HTML file:

1. Content of the page
2. Information about the page (for right now just how to style it).

In creating web pages we differentiate between these two areas using the &lt;head&gt; and &lt;body&gt; elements. These elements are important for creating maintainable code but will also be useful for other things as well. The &lt;head&gt; element contains all the information about the page, also sometimes called **metadata**.  The &lt;body&gt; element contains all the content for a web page.

Outline of the structure of your web page:

<pre>
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
	&lt;head&gt;
		&lt;style&gt;
    		&lt;!--Styling Goes Here--&gt;
		&lt;/style&gt;
	&lt;/head&gt;

	&lt;body&gt;
		&lt;!--Content Goes Here--&gt;
	&lt;/body&gt;

&lt;/html&gt;
</pre>


# Do This

* Add a &lt;head&gt; element surrounding the styling for the web page.
* Add a &lt;body&gt; element surrounding the content for the web page.

